# Dataset

This project uses the **Book-Crossing Dataset** to develop a hybrid book recommendation system combining Content-Based Filtering and Collaborative Filtering.

The dataset contains anonymized user information, book metadata, and user-book rating interactions. It was originally collected by Cai-Nicolas Ziegler from the Book-Crossing online community and is widely used for recommender system research.

The dataset contains:

- **278,858 users**
- **271,379 books**
- **1,149,780 ratings**

## Dataset Files

The Book-Crossing dataset consists of three main CSV files:

| File | Description | Rows (raw) |
|---|---|---|
| `BX-Books.csv` | Book metadata including ISBN, title, author, publication year, publisher, and cover image links | ~271,000 |
| `BX-Users.csv` | User information including anonymized User-ID, location, and age (when available) | ~279,000 |
| `BX-Book-Ratings.csv` | User-book interactions containing User-ID, ISBN, and ratings from 0–10 | ~1,150,000 |

## Dataset Source

The dataset used in this project was obtained from Kaggle:

https://www.kaggle.com/code/ruchi798/book-crossing-starter-notebook-and-eda/notebook

The Kaggle version is based on the original Book-Crossing Dataset collected by:

Ziegler, C.-N., McNee, S. M., Konstan, J. A., & Lausen, G. (2005).  
*Improving Recommendation Lists Through Topic Diversification.*  
Proceedings of the 14th International World Wide Web Conference (WWW '05).

Original dataset source:
http://www2.informatik.uni-freiburg.de/~cziegler/BX/

## Dataset Availability

The CSV files are **not included in this repository** because of their size (~120 MB total). GitHub has file size limitations, and storing large datasets directly in the repository is not recommended.

To run this project:

1. Download the dataset files.
2. Place the CSV files inside this `data/` folder.
3. Run the preprocessing and recommendation scripts.

## Format Notes

- Delimiter: `;` (semicolon)
- Text fields are enclosed with quotation marks (`"`)
- Encoding: `latin-1` (ISO-8859-1)

The `BX-Book-Ratings.csv` file contains two types of ratings:

- **Explicit ratings:** Values from 1–10 where users provided a rating.
- **Implicit interactions:** Value `0`, meaning the user interacted with a book but did not provide an explicit rating.

The preprocessing pipeline removes implicit ratings before training the collaborative filtering model.

